inProgress.subTitle: The Race to Fix Our Food System and Save Our Climate
inProgress.fullTitle: We Are Eating the Earth: The Race to Fix Our Food System and Save Our Climate
inProgress.author: Michael Grunwald

books.title: The AI Con
books.subTitle: How to Fight Big Tech's Hype and Create the Future We Want
books.fullTitle: The AI Con: How to Fight Big Tech's Hype and Create the Future We Want
books.author: Emily M. Bender & Alex Hanna
books.thoughts: A thoughtful look at the issues related to AI and all the hype and doom its backers are pushing.

books.title: Acquired Taste
books.author: Clay McLeod Chapman
books.thoughts: I found a lot of the stories in this to be weird. Maybe it just wasn’t for me.

books.title: Inferno
books.subTitle: The World at War, 1939-1945
books.author: Max Hastings
books.thoughts: Fantastic book on World War II. Hastings goes through the different fronts and happenings in Asia, the Pacific, and of course Britain and Western Europe.

books.title: Automatic Noodle
books.author: Annalee Newitz
books.thoughts: This was a fun story.

books.title: Why Fascists Fear Teachers
books.subTitle: Public Education and the Future of Democracy
books.fullTitle: Why Fascists Fear Teachers: Public Education and the Future of Democracy
books.author: Randi Weingarten
books.thoughts: A thoughtful take on the power of teachers and multitude of ways the right is trying to undermine them. It did a good job putting into words how the attacks work and why it’s more important now, more than ever to push back for good education.

books.title: Stories Are Weapons
books.subTitle: Psychological Warfare and the American Mind
books.fullTitle: Stories Are Weapons: Psychological Warfare and the American Mind
books.author: Annalee Newitz
books.thoughts: A interesting, if not depressing look at the different ways we’re going to have to combat misinformation and disinformation in the coming years.

books.title: Wake Up and Open Your Eyes
books.fullTitle: Wake Up and Open Your Eyes
books.author: Clay McLeod Chapman
books.thoughts: A creepy book that fits in well with the current political climate.

books.title: Ghost Eaters
books.author: Clay McLeod Chapman
books.thoughts: A creepy story that fits well in the Halloween season.

books.title: Whisper Down the Lane
books.author: Clay McLeod Chapman
books.thoughts: A fast read. Creepy with a whole lot of twists and turns. I enjoyed it.

books.title: Just Keep Buying
books.subTitle: Proven ways to save money and build your wealth
books.fullTitle: Just Keep Buying: Proven ways to save money and build your wealth
books.author: Nick Maggiulli
books.thoughts: Thoughtful advice when planning for retirement and other investment goals.

books.title: Billion Dollar Whale
books.subTitle: The Man Who Fooled Wall Street, Hollywood, and the World
books.fullTitle: Billion Dollar Whale: The Man Who Fooled Wall Street, Hollywood, and the World
books.author: Bradley Hope & Tom Wright
books.thoughts: A fascinating deep dive into the 1MDB scandal and the characters involved. It still amazes me how many people will ignore giant red flags for a quick buck.

books.title: Apple in China
books.subTitle: The Capture of the World's Greatest Company
books.fullTitle: Apple in China: The Capture of the World's Greatest Company
books.author: Patrick McGee
books.thoughts: This was a fascinating look at the Apple's manufacturing history and how China has captured so much of it, and in turn, Apple itself.

books.title: Our Dollar, Your Problem
books.subTitle: An Insider's View of Seven Turbulent Decades of Global Finance, and the Road Ahead
books.fullTitle: Our Dollar, Your Problem: An Insider's View of Seven Turbulent Decades of Global Finance, and the Road Ahead
books.author: Kenneth Rogoff
books.thoughts: An interesting look at the US Dollar and how it has maintained its place as the “global currency”. Some of the warnings have proven rather indicative of our current economic situation.

books.title: The Wealth Ladder
books.subTitle: Proven Strategies for Every Step of Your Financial Life
books.fullTitle: The Wealth Ladder: Proven Strategies for Every Step of Your Financial Life
books.author: Nick Maggiulli
books.thoughts: A bit of a look and some help for investing and increasing your wealth.

books.title: Play Nice
books.subTitle: The Rise, Fall, and Future of Blizzard Entertainment
books.fullTitle: Play Nice: The Rise, Fall, and Future of Blizzard Entertainment
books.author: Jason Schreier
books.thoughts: A good look back at the history of Blizzard as well as the struggles and trouble they got into. Made me reminisce about my time playing WoW.

books.title: The Hero of Ages
books.author: Brandon Sanderson
books.thoughts: A good ending to a fantastic trilogy. Action, suspense, drama, and most importantly, a fitting conclusion.

books.title: Zen Mind, Beginner's Mind
books.author: Shunryu Suzuki
books.thoughts: I've been considering meditation and this was one of the recommendations. I'm not sure how much I really got out of this.

books.title: A Physical Education
books.subTitle: How I Escaped Diet Culture and Gained the Power of Lifting
books.fullTitle: A Physical Education: How I Escaped Diet Culture and Gained the Power of Lifting
books.author: Casey Johnston
books.thoughts: This inspired me to focus again on lifting. Would recommend.

books.title: The Well of Ascension
books.author: Brandon Sanderson
books.thoughts: Another good book in the trilogy that definitely makes me want to finish it.

books.title: Mistborn
books.author: Brandon Sanderson
books.thoughts: This was my first Brandon Sanderson novel and I really enjoyed it. Good characters and a gripping story.

books.title: Down with the System
books.subTitle: A Memoir (of Sorts)
books.fullTitle: Down with the System: A Memoir (of Sorts)
books.author: Serj Tankian
books.thoughts: An interesting look at the System of a Down's frontman. He talked about his music, his life, his Armenian heritage and political activism.

books.title: Chokepoints
books.subTitle: American Power in the Age of Economic Warfare
books.fullTitle: Chokepoints: American Power in the Age of Economic Warfare
books.author: Edward Fishman
books.thoughts: This was an incredibly fascinating look at how America and its allies used economic weapons as a way to wage war, not with troops, but by going after our adversary’s economies.

books.title: Rise of the Warrior Cop
books.subTitle: The Militarization of America's Police Forces
books.fullTitle: Rise of the Warrior Cop: The Militarization of America's Police Forces
books.author: Radley Balko
books.thoughts: This was an in-depth look at how the police have started to use SWAT teams far more often through various administrations.

books.title: Bad Company
books.subTitle: Private Equity and the Death of the American Dream
books.fullTitle: Bad Company: Private Equity and the Death of the American Dream
books.author: Megan Greenwell
books.thoughts: This was a good look at how private equity has been destroying retail, hospitals & healthcare, the journalism industry, and residential housing. It balances the overarching problem with personal stories in a way that makes you realize the scope of the problem.

books.title: Under Alien Skies
books.subTitle: A Sightseer's Guide to the Universe
books.fullTitle: Under Alien Skies: A Sightseer's Guide to the Universe
books.author: Philip Plait
books.thoughts: Whenever I read about space, I always feel so small. Philip does a fantastic job talking about the various planets, moons, and other environments in space and what they would look like. It was informative and incredibly fascinating.

books.title: The Exvangelicals
books.subTitle: Loving, Living, and Leaving the White Evangelical Church
books.fullTitle: The Exvangelicals: Loving, Living, and Leaving the White Evangelical Church
books.author: Sarah McCammon
books.thoughts: An interesting look at the Evangelical and former Evangelical community from someone who lived through it.

books.title: When the Moon Hits Your Eye
books.fullTitle: When the Moon Hits Your Eye
books.author: John Scalzi
books.thoughts: Another good one by Scalzi. It was playful, funny and enjoyable.

books.title: The Wrong Stuff
books.subTitle: How the Soviet Space Program Crashed and Burned
books.fullTitle: The Wrong Stuff: How the Soviet Space Program Crashed and Burned
books.author: John Strausbaugh
books.thoughts: I knew the Soviet space program was never as good as they claimed it to be. I never realized how shoe-string it really was. This was a great read and look at how the Soviet space program got off the ground and operated through and beyond the USSR’s collapse.

books.title: The Alignment Problem
books.subTitle: Machine Learning and Human Values
books.fullTitle: The Alignment Problem: Machine Learning and Human Values
books.author: Brian Christian
books.thoughts: An interesting look at how we interact and train AI and LLMs. Sometimes dry, but still insightful.

books.title: Where Nobody Knows Your Name
books.subTitle: Life in the Minor Leagues of Baseball
books.fullTitle: Where Nobody Knows Your Name: Life in the Minor Leagues of Baseball
books.author: John Feinstein
books.thoughts: This was an interesting look at the minor leagues and how players, managers, umpires, and even broadcasters handle being in a competitive league where almost everyone wants to move up.

books.title: Homo Deus
books.subTitle: A Brief History of Tomorrow
books.fullTitle: Homo Deus: A Brief History of Tomorrow
books.author: Yuval Noah Harari
books.thoughts: It was a little dry and felt a little disorganized.

books.title: The Staircase in the Woods
books.author: Chuck Wendig
books.thoughts: Another great one by Chuck Wendig. Just the right mix of thriller and horror to leave you on the edge of your seat wanting to read more.

books.title: Ancillary Mercy
books.author: Ann Leckie
books.thoughts: This was a good ending to the series. It was enjoyable with some good twists and a solid finish.

books.title: Doom Guy
books.subTitle: Life in First Person
books.fullTitle: Doom Guy: Life in First Person
books.author: John Romero
books.thoughts: I loved DOOM and this was a great read (listen?) to John Romero's history of getting into game development. It's amazing to hear how they pushed the needle for video games with fantastic games wringing maximum performance from early computers.

books.title: More Money Than God
books.subTitle: Hedge Funds and the Making of a New Elite
books.fullTitle: More Money Than God: Hedge Funds and the Making of a New Elite
books.author: Sebastian Mallaby
books.thoughts: The book was kind of dry but provided an interesting look at the history of index funds with a good comparison to investment banks.

books.title: Dark Wire
books.subTitle: The Incredible True Story of the Largest Sting Operation Ever
books.fullTitle: Dark Wire: The Incredible True Story of the Largest Sting Operation Ever
books.author: Joseph Cox
books.thoughts: This was an incredibly detailed look into what was and impressive sting operation by the FBI.

books.title: Farenheit 182
books.subTitle: A Memoir
books.author: Mark Hoppus & Dan Ozzi
books.thoughts: I loved blink-182 in high school and college (still do), they headlined my first concert. It was fun memoir to read about Mark and his journey from a kid to one of the biggest stars of the pop punk genre.

books.title: Ancillary Sword
books.author: Ann Leckie
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this, I felt it was better and more suspenseful than Ancillary Justice in all the right ways. Makes me look forward to finishing the trilogy.

books.title: The Sirens' Call
books.subTitle: How Attention Became the World's Most Endangered Resource
books.fullTitle: The Sirens' Call: How Attention Became the World's Most Endangered Resource
books.author: Chris Hayes
books.thoughts: Some interesting thoughts about how companies and people try to capture our attention. Most of it felt pretty obvious to me and didn’t think anything here was all that revealing.

books.title: Murder the Truth
books.subTitle: Fear, the First Amendment, and a Secret Campaign to Protect the Powerful
books.fullTitle: Murder the Truth: Fear, the First Amendment, and a Secret Campaign to Protect the Powerful
books.author: David Enrich
books.thoughts: This was a good read looking at the history of libel law in the US. It did a good job talking about how we got the law we have as well as how the rich and powerful are trying to overturn the rules and laws in place. For those who want to make sure we have the ability to hold the rich and powerful to account, this is a good book to understand why NYT v Sullivan is so important.

books.title: Winning Fixes Everything
books.subTitle: How Baseball's Brightest Minds Created Sports' Biggest Mess
books.fullTitle: Winning Fixes Everything: How Baseball's Brightest Minds Created Sports' Biggest Mess
books.author: Evan Drellich
books.thoughts: This was an interesting dive into the 2017 Houston Astros as well as how they dove into analytics after Jim Crane bought the team in 2011.

books.title: Thinking in Systems
books.author: Donella Meadows
books.thoughts: This was an interesting, albeit non-in-depth look at how various systems work and some of the traps involved, as well as how to overcome them.

books.title: Where the Axe is Buried
books.author: Ray Nayler
books.thoughts: An interesting story. Parts of it felt a little too close to home in the current political climate. A little too dystopian in some aspects, but enjoyable.

books.title: Ancillary Justice
books.author: Ann Leckie
books.thoughts: Started off a little slow. Other than its pacing, it was enjoyable.

books.title: Operation Paperclip
books.subTitle: The Secret Intelligence Program That Brought Nazi Scientists to America
books.fullTitle: Operation Paperclip: The Secret Intelligence Program That Brought Nazi Scientists to America
books.author: Annie Jacobsen
books.thoughts: This was a fascinating, but somber read. It is shameful how much the US Government was willing to look past, or actively hide with regards to the scientists brought over from Nazi Germany.

books.title: Character Limit
books.subTitle: How Elon Musk Destroyed Twitter
books.fullTitle: Character Limit: How Elon Musk Destroyed Twitter
books.author: Kate Conger & Ryan Mac
books.thoughts: I know Twitter could be a hellhole, but I enjoyed it. This book did a good job talking about and documenting how Elon purchased and ruined the social network.

books.title: Autocracy, Inc.
books.subTitle: The Dictators Who Want to Run the World
books.fullTitle: Autocracy, Inc.: The Dictators Who Want to Run the World
books.author: Anne Applebaum
books.thoughts: This was a scary look at the autocratic world, and how so many of the things happening in America. It's a short book and I'd recommend it. It puts the current situation in the US even more frightening.

books.title: Madoff
books.subTitle: The Final Word
books.author: Richard Behar
books.thoughts: This was an interesting look at the largest ponzi scheme in history and the characters involved. It provided a look at Madoff and what he did and how he got it to last as long as it did.

books.title: Picks and Shovels
books.author: Cory Doctorow
books.thoughts: Another good one from Cory Doctorow. Had some good twists and kept me on the edge of my seat.

books.title: When McKinsey Comes to Town
books.subTitle: The Hidden Influence of the World's Most Powerful Consulting Firm
books.fullTitle: When McKinsey Comes to Town: The Hidden Influence of the World's Most Powerful Consulting Firm
books.author: Walt Bogdanich & Michael Forsythe
books.thoughts: This provided some good insight into McKinsey which made me angrier the more I read. Their callous disregard for how their work affects people is just cruel. It was enlightening and I feel important to understand how much McKinsey and companies like McKinsey cause the harm that they do.

books.title: The Splendid and the Vile
books.subTitle: A Saga of Churchill, Family and Defiance During the Blitz
books.fullTitle: The Splendid and the Vile: A Saga of Churchill, Family and Defiance During the Blitz
books.author: Erik Larson
books.thoughts: Another interesting read by Erik Larson. It was interesting reading about Churchill and the challenges he faced with the Blitz. I knew it was bad, but this provided some insight into it and the UK government’s handling of it. The only thing I wasn’t sure of was the sidebars into his family’s love affairs.

books.title: In the Garden of Beasts
books.subTitle: Love, Terror, and an American Family in Hitler's Berlin
books.fullTitle: In the Garden of Beasts: Love, Terror, and an American Family in Hitler's Berlin
books.author: Erik Larson
books.thoughts: An interesting look at the rise of Hitler and Nazi Germany through the career of the US’ ambassador to Germany. Larson does a good job of documenting Dodd’s challenges and mindset while navigating the rise of Hitler.

books.title: The Bound Worlds
books.author: Megan E. O'Keefe
books.thoughts: I enjoyed the book and the twists and turns. It was a good ending to the series.

books.title: The Fractured Dark
books.author: Megan E. O'Keefe
books.thoughts: A good continuation to the story and the world she built into the first book. This had some good twists as well.

books.title: The Gates of Europe
books.subTitle: A History of Ukraine
books.fullTitle: The Gates of Europe: A History of Ukraine
books.author: Serhii Plokhy
books.thoughts: This was an interesting and in depth look at the history of Ukraine as far back as the Greek and Roman Empires. It was written in 2015 so the current war is not included, but the run up to it was. It was captivating and gave me an idea of what Ukraine has been through as well as how we got to where we are today.

books.title: Atomic Habits
books.author: James Clear
books.thoughts: Some useful tips on helping you improve yourself and your habits.

books.title: Deep Work
books.subTitle: Rules for Focused Success in a Distracted World
books.fullTitle: Deep Work: Rules for Focused Success in a Distracted World
books.author: Cal Newport
books.thoughts: Another good book by Cal Newport with some thoughts about how to regain focus and do good work.

books.title: Slow Productivity
books.subTitle: The Lost Art of Accomplishment Without Burnout
books.fullTitle: Slow Productivity: The Lost Art of Accomplishment Without Burnout
books.author: Cal Newport
books.thoughts: Another interesting book by Cal Newport that proposes some ideas for helping you stay productive without killing yourself.

books.title: The Blighted Stars
books.author: Megan E. O'Keefe
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this. It’s a fascinating world with a good story set up for the trilogy.

books.title: The Death of Expertise
books.subTitle: The Campaign Against Established Knowledge and Why It Matters
books.fullTitle: The Death of Expertise: The Campaign Against Established Knowledge and Why It Matters
books.author: Tom Nichols
books.thoughts: This was a detailed, but depressing look at how we as a society have scorned experts and mistaken our own knowledge as expertise. It explains a lot about where we are as a society.

books.title: Last to Leave the Room
books.author: Caitlin Starling
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this. It was an interesting story with some good twists.

books.title: Digital Minimalism
books.subTitle: Choosing a Focused Life in a Noisy World
books.fullTitle: Digital Minimalism: Choosing a Focused Life in a Noisy World
books.author: Cal Newport
books.thoughts: Cal Newport makes some good points in this book how technology and social media can overcrowd our lives. While I’m not sure about everything, there’s some helpful tips and advice for getting a better hold of our time and attention in this distracting digital world.

books.title: Challenger
books.subTitle: A True Story of Heroism and Disaster on the Edge of Space
books.fullTitle: Challenger: A True Story of Heroism and Disaster on the Edge of Space
books.author: Adam Higginbotham
books.thoughts: I loved this. It was a great read talking about the development of the Space Shuttle as well as all the details that led to the Challenger disaster. It was in depth and even provided me with more details that I didn’t realize.

books.title: System Collapse
books.author: Martha Wells
books.thoughts: Another solid story in the series. Going to have to wait until the next, sadly.

books.title: Fugitive Telemetry
books.author: Martha Wells
books.thoughts: Another solid book in the series, this time with a true crime kind of vibe.

books.title: Network Effect
books.author: Martha Wells
books.thoughts: Another good story in the series. Longer that the earlier books, but captivating and enjoyable.

books.title: The Book of Accidents
books.author: Chuck Wendig
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this. It had some good twists and turns with the right amount of creepiness I would expect from Wendig. Also, if you’re a Stephen King fan, you’d really enjoy this.

books.title: Nuclear War
books.subTitle: A Scenario
books.author: Annie Jacobsen
books.thoughts: This was a scary read. It was incredibly fascinating to see how nuclear war might play out in the real world and how awful it is and how you just can't win. I'd recommend it.

books.title: Battle Cry of Freedom
books.subTitle: The Civil War Era
books.fullTitle: Battle Cry of Freedom: The Civil War Era
books.author: James M. McPherson
books.thoughts: This was a fascinating, albeit long read into the history of the Civil War. It provided a lot of details that I had not fully known and I would recommend it to anyone interested in history.

books.title: Home
books.subTitle: Habitat, Range, Niche, Territory
books.author: Martha Wells
books.thoughts: I’m not entirely sure I understand this short story. It’s possible future books might provide some light on it though.

books.title: Exit Strategy
books.author: Martha Wells
books.thoughts: Another solid book in the Murderbot series.

books.title: Rogue Protocol
books.author: Martha Wells
books.thoughts: This is the third book in the Murderbot series and the best one I’ve read so far. Good story and a fast, enjoyable read.

books.title: Artificial Condition
books.author: Martha Wells
books.thoughts: Another good short story set in the Murderbot universe. Fast read and enjoyable.

books.title: All Systems Red
books.author: Martha Wells
books.thoughts: This was a much faster read than I anticipated. It was still a fun little sci fi story I’d recommend.

books.title: The Mercy of Gods
books.author: James S.A. Corey
books.thoughts: Had a hard time making sure I didn’t pre-judge this based on The Expanse series but this was definitely a solid sci fi story. Interesting premise and characters that left me wanting to read more.

books.title: Zero Days
books.author: Ruth Ware
books.thoughts: This felt a little different than what I normally read, but it was suspenseful and fun to read.

books.title: The Good Neighbor
books.subTitle: The Life and Work of Fred Rogers
books.fullTitle: The Good Neighbor: The Life and Work of Fred Rogers
books.author: Maxwell King
books.thoughts: I idolized Mr. Rogers as a child and I thought this was a very fitting biography of him. I’ve heard so much about him growing up and this was a nice look into who he was as a person.

books.title: Station Eleven
books.author: Emily St. John Mandel
books.thoughts: An interesting story that in some cases felt like it hit a little too close to 2020, but was still enjoyable with a good amount of suspense to want to know what happens next.

books.title: The Demon of Unrest
books.subTitle: A Saga of Hubris, Heartbreak, and Heroism at the Dawn of the Civil War
books.fullTitle: The Demon of Unrest: A Saga of Hubris, Heartbreak, and Heroism at the Dawn of the Civil War
books.author: Erik Larson
books.thoughts: This was an interesting read describing the run up to the Civil War and the fall of Fort Sumter. It provides interesting insights into the characters involved and some of their motivations.

books.title: Liar in a Crowded Theater
books.subTitle: Freedom of Speech in a World of Misinformation
books.fullTitle: Liar in a Crowded Theater: Freedom of Speech in a World of Misinformation
books.author: Jeff Kosseff
books.thoughts: This was an interesting look at how strong our first amendment protections are and why, despite the constant threats of mis and disinformation, is such a good thing. It might be easy to want the government to step in, but Jeff Kosseff does a good job explaining why that’s not such a good thing and offers some better alternatives.

books.title: Gentle Writing Advice
books.subTitle: How to Be a Writer Without Destroying Yourself
books.fullTitle: Gentle Writing Advice: How to Be a Writer Without Destroying Yourself
books.author: Chuck Wendig
books.thoughts: A lot of insight into his thoughts as a writer and some tips to help me figure out what my process should be. It was helpful to read about his thoughts on the craft.

books.title: The Internet Con
books.subTitle: How to Seize the Means of Computation
books.fullTitle: The Internet Con: How to Seize the Means of Computation
books.author: Cory Doctorow
books.thoughts: I appreciate Cory Doctorow’s writing about tech and this is no different. He does a good job explaining the issues with the tech giants and how they got so large and powerful, as well as some ways to limit their power and give us more power in the process.

books.title: The Firm
books.author: John Grisham
books.thoughts: This didn’t necessarily feel like something I normally read, but it was still a captivating story. The characters felt believable and there were points I didn’t want to put it down.

books.title: The Blood Telegram
books.subTitle: Nixon, Kissinger, and a Forgotten Genocide
books.fullTitle: The Blood Telegram: Nixon, Kissinger, and a Forgotten Genocide
books.author: Gary J. Bass
books.thoughts: This was an informative read about events I was unaware of. It also provided a look into the Nixon White House that clearly matches the reputation of Nixon and Kissinger.

books.title: Wayward
books.author: Chuck Wendig
books.thoughts: I loved Wanderers and Wayward is a great sequel to it. The characters and the story is gripping, captivating and enjoyable.

books.title: The Bezzle
books.author: Cory Doctorow
books.thoughts: It was an interesting story with good characters and a nice level of suspense. Quick read as well.

books.title: Lost Cause
books.author: Cory Doctorow
books.thoughts: Interesting story with a hopeful look towards the future dealing with climate and intolerance.

books.title: Red Team Blues
books.author: Cory Doctorow
books.thoughts: A fast read and a good story. If you’re a fan of Doctorow’s writing, you’ll like this.

books.title: Wanderers
books.author: Chuck Wendig
books.thoughts: I really enjoyed this one. The characters were interesting and it had a good level of suspense with an interesting story to back it up.

books.title: Holly
books.author: Stephen King
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this. Was a little different than I expected, but not in a bad way.

books.title: State of Fear
books.author: Michael Crichton
books.thoughts: Interesting story but the anti-climate change messaging rubbed me the wrong way, even considering the time it was written.

books.title: Under the Dome
books.author: Stephen King
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this. Was a captivating story that made me kept wanting to read more.

books.title: Making It So
books.subTitle: A Memoir
books.author: Patrick Stewart
books.thoughts: An interesting look back at Patrick Stewart’s life.

books.title: The Android’s Dream
books.author: John Scalzi
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this. It had a good mix of humor with John Scalzi’s excellent storytelling.

books.title: The Stand
books.author: Stephen King
books.thoughts: I really enjoyed this. Parts of it felt a little too on the nose after 2020, but the characters and story was captivating.

books.author: Stephen King
books.thoughts: I really enjoyed this one. It had an interesting premise and the suspense kept me going throughout.

books.title: Starship Troopers
books.author: Robert A. Heinlein
books.thoughts: To be blunt, I’m not sure why so many speak so highly of this.

books.title: Salem's Lot
books.author: Stephen King
books.thoughts: It was a little predictable in some aspects, but I enjoyed it.

books.title: Catch-22
books.author: Joseph Heller
books.thoughts: This whole book made me chuckle at some of its ridiculousness. Feels a little like Seinfeld meets the madness of war.

books.title: Pragmatic Test-Driven Development in C# and .NET
books.fullTitle: Pragmatic Test-Driven Development in C# and .NET
books.author: Adam Tibi
books.thoughts: This was a good look into test-driven development. Adam did a good job explaining it and showed some examples for those with an idea of what TDD is, and for those with no knowledge of it.

books.title: Sea of Tranquility
books.author: Emily St. John Mandel
books.thoughts: An interesting premise and a fun story. Was a quick read and enjoyable.

books.title: Parallel Programming and Concurrency with C# 10 and .NET 6
books.fullTitle: Parallel Programming and Concurrency with C# 10 and .NET 6
books.author: Alvin Ashcraft
books.thoughts: Was informative. Learned a bunch, but was tough to wrap my head around some of it. Figure more will make sense as I apply what I learned and write code.

books.title: Easy Money
books.subTitle: Cryptocurrency, Casino Capitalism, and the Golden Age of Fraud
books.fullTitle: Easy Money: Cryptocurrency, Casino Capitalism, and the Golden Age of Fraud
books.author: Ben McKenzie
books.thoughts: I had already learned most of the history of much of the crypto-nonsense from other sources, but this was a good refresher. It does a good job pointing out the many similarities between crypto, Ponzi schemes and gambling.

books.title: Grit
books.subTitle: The Power of Passion and Perseverance
books.fullTitle: Grit: The Power of Passion and Perseverance
books.author: Angela Duckworth
books.thoughts: It was an interesting read and gives me thoughts on how to improve myself and rethink my outlook on life.

books.title: The War That Made the Roman Empire
books.subTitle: Antony, Cleopatra, and Octavian at Actium
books.fullTitle: The War That Made the Roman Empire: Antony, Cleopatra, and Octavian at Actium
books.author: Barry Strauss
books.thoughts: Another fantastic book documenting the battle between Octavian and Antony that led to the end of the Roman Republic. Strauss does a fantastic job of laying out the events as they happened with all the characters involved.

books.title: The Storm Before the Storm
books.subTitle: The Beginning of the End of the Roman Republic
books.fullTitle: The Storm Before the Storm: The Beginning of the End of the Roman Republic
books.author: Mike Duncan
books.thoughts: This was an interesting look at the last years of the Roman Republic before it became the Roman Empire. I lot of it I didn’t know and Duncan did a good job navigating the different events and characters involved.

books.title: The Pale Blue Eye
books.author: Louis Bayard
books.thoughts: The book was slow at times and seemingly wandered off track. The finish was definitely a good one though.

books.title: Humble Pi
books.subTitle: When Math Goes Wrong in the Real World
books.fullTitle: Humble Pi: When Math Goes Wrong in the Real World
books.author: Matt Parker
books.thoughts: I really enjoyed this read. Matt had a good sense of humor and it was interesting to realize some of the many ways math affects us without us realizing until it goes wrong.

books.title: American Whitelash
books.subTitle: A Changing Nation and the Cost of Progress
books.fullTitle: American Whitelash: A Changing Nation and the Cost of Progress
books.author: Wesley Lowery
books.thoughts: This was an interesting, if depressing read. It’s sad to see how racist we still are as a nation.

books.title: Emotional Intelligence 2.0
books.author: Dr. Travis Bradberry & Dr. Jean Greaves
books.thoughts: I was given this book by my job to help with my career trajectory. It was an interesting look at how we handle ourselves and gave good advice on how to improve our interactions with others.

books.title: A City on Mars
books.subTitle: Can We Settle Space, Should We Settle Space, and Have We Really Thought This Through?
books.fullTitle: A City on Mars: Can We Settle Space, Should We Settle Space, and Have We Really Thought This Through?
books.author: Kelly and Zach Weinersmith
books.thoughts: This was a fantastic look at the various things we’d have to look at as a society to actually settle space. It’s written in an easy to understand way and really made me think about the near future of space exploration and settlement.

books.title: The Creative ACT
books.subTitle: A Way of Being
books.fullTitle: The Creative ACT: A Way of Being
books.author: Rick Rubin
books.thoughts: As someone who is trying to explore his creative side more, I appreciated the insights provided.

books.title: Anvil of Stars
books.author: Greg Bear
books.thoughts: I didn’t like this as much as the first book in the series, but I’m having a hard time articulating why. It wasn’t bad, just didn’t live up to The Forge of God.

books.title: The Forge of God
books.author: Greg Bear
books.thoughts: I enjoyed the story. It was interesting and brought a good mix of thriller and science fiction.

books.title: The Poison Eaters and Other Stories
books.fullTitle: The Poison Eaters and Other Stories
books.author: Holly Black
books.thoughts: I enjoyed some of the stories. Others, not as much

books.title: Subprime Attention Crisis
books.subTitle: Advertising and the Time Bomb at the Heart of the Internet
books.fullTitle: Subprime Attention Crisis: Advertising and the Time Bomb at the Heart of the Internet
books.author: Tim Hwang
books.thoughts: This was an interesting, though kind of dry read about some of the dangers that lurk in the world of online advertising.

books.title: Be Useful
books.subTitle: Seven Tools for Life
books.fullTitle: Be Useful: Seven Tools for Life
books.author: Arnold Schwarzenegger
books.thoughts: It was an interesting read. Arnold talked a bit about his own life and gave some useful tips on how to do better to reach your goals.

books.title: Extremely Online
books.subTitle: The Untold Story of Fame, Influence, and Power on the Internet
books.fullTitle: Extremely Online: The Untold Story of Fame, Influence, and Power on the Internet
books.author: Taylor Lorenz
books.thoughts: This was an interesting read about the creator culture of the internet. It also happened to remind me I will never understand pop culture.

books.title: Black River Orchard
books.author: Chuck Wendig
books.thoughts: I really enjoyed the story. It had interesting characters and it kept me on the edge of my seat.

books.title: Number Go Up
books.subTitle: Inside Crypto's Wild Rise and Staggering Fall
books.fullTitle: Number Go Up: Inside Crypto's Wild Rise and Staggering Fall
books.author: Zeke Faux
books.thoughts: There was one quote that stood out to me: "The crypto bubble wasn’t as dumb as you think. It was even dumber.” This book goes into the rise of crypto and NFTs and how obvious it should have been that much of it was kind of scammy at best.

books.title: Your Face Belongs to Us
books.subTitle: A Secretive Startup's Quest to End Privacy as We Know It
books.fullTitle: Your Face Belongs to Us: A Secretive Startup's Quest to End Privacy as We Know It
books.author: Kashmir Hill
books.thoughts: Yeah, this book scared me a bit. Hill did a great job talking about the history of facial recognition, what Clearview AI has done for it, and the risks moving forward.

books.title: Starter Villain
books.author: John Scalzi
books.thoughts: This was a fun book to read. I enjoyed the story and the characters.

books.title: On Writing
books.subTitle: A Memoir of the Craft
books.fullTitle: On Writing: A Memoir of the Craft
books.author: Stephen King
books.thoughts: As someone who is starting to write more, I enjoyed his thoughts on his career and advice for other writers.

books.title: Coders
books.subTitle: The Making of a New Tribe and the Remaking of the World
books.fullTitle: Coders: The Making of a New Tribe and the Remaking of the World
books.author: Clive Thompson
books.thoughts: I saw a lot of myself while reading this. It’s a good book that goes into both the good and the bad of what we’ve built with computers.

books.title: Team of Rivals
books.subTitle: The Political Genius of Abraham Lincoln
books.fullTitle: Team of Rivals: The Political Genius of Abraham Lincoln
books.author: Doris Kearns Goodwin
books.thoughts: I found this book to be incredibly interesting. It was a great look into Lincoln’s political life and how he ran his presidency. The author did a great job of talking about how Lincoln went about making the Emancipation Proclamation as well as getting the 13th amendment passed to end slavery once and for all.

books.title: Trigger Warning
books.author: Neil Gaiman
books.thoughts: This book is hard to judge since it’s a collection of short stories. Some I liked, some I didn’t, others I was “meh” on.

books.title: Talking to Strangers
books.subTitle: What We Should Know about the People We Don't Know
books.fullTitle: Talking to Strangers: What We Should Know about the People We Don't Know
books.author: Malcolm Gladwell
books.thoughts: Reading reminded me how hard it is to know exactly how hard it can be to interact with strangers. It was an interesting read talking about how these struggles have had dire consequences. The biggest takeaway I took from it kind of echoes the classic “trust, but verify” and that empathy can be helpful.

books.title: Packing for Mars
books.subTitle: The Curious Science of Life in the Void
books.fullTitle: Packing for Mars: The Curious Science of Life in the Void
books.author: Mary Roach
books.thoughts: I actually really enjoyed this. It went into a lot of the smaller details of all the things that go into space travel many don’t think about.

books.title: A History of the World in 6 Glasses
books.fullTitle: A History of the World in 6 Glasses
books.author: Tom Standage
books.thoughts: This was an enjoyable and informative look back at how different drinks came to determine so much of our history of a species. I really enjoyed it.

books.title: Dead Wake
books.subTitle: The Last Crossing of the Lusitania
books.fullTitle: Dead Wake: The Last Crossing of the Lusitania
books.author: Erik Larson
books.thoughts: This was a fascinating look from both those on the Lusitania and from the captain of the U-Boat that sunk the Lusitania. It was compelling even though you already knew the ending.

books.title: Shutdown
books.subTitle: How Covid Shook the World's Economy
books.fullTitle: Shutdown: How Covid Shook the World's Economy
books.author: Adam Tooze
books.thoughts: I found his look back at the different world governments’ response to COVID to be interesting. It was in-depth and provided some good details. I did feel like it bounced around a little more than I would’ve expected which made it a little difficult to follow.

books.title: Out of Office
books.subTitle: The Big Problem and Bigger Promise of Working from Home
books.fullTitle: Out of Office: The Big Problem and Bigger Promise of Working from Home
books.author: Charlie Warzel & Anne Helen Petersen
books.thoughts: This was an interesting read and definitely follows close to the current return to office back and forth we’re seeing. It did a good job going into why that’s not necessarily the full picture or what we should be looking at, but rather, finding a better work-life balance for everyone.

books.title: Learning Patterns
books.author: Lydia Hallie & Addy Osmani
books.thoughts: The first part of the book gave some good overview of different dev patterns. The rest of the book gave some great insights into better ways to build and make sites more performant. Dangerous because it made me consider some redesigning of my site.

books.title: Bullshit Jobs
books.author: David Graeber
books.thoughts: There are many memorable stories and anecdotes in this. David does a decent job of going through what bullshit jobs are and how we got here.

books.title: The Terraformers
books.author: Annalee Newitz
books.thoughts: This was a fun sci-fi story. I felt like there was more that could’ve been explored a bit with the characters but I still enjoyed it.

books.title: Twilight of the Gods
books.subTitle: War in the Western Pacific, 1944-1945
books.fullTitle: Twilight of the Gods: War in the Western Pacific, 1944-1945
books.author: Ian W. Toll
books.thoughts: This entire trilogy was well-written and incredibly interesting. This book was no different. It was interesting to read about the Allies’ final push and how long it took Japan to accept defeat. It was jaw-dropping and sobering how many lives on both sides were lost because of it all.

books.title: The Conquering Tide
books.subTitle: War in the Pacific Islands, 1942-1944
books.fullTitle: The Conquering Tide: War in the Pacific Islands, 1942-1944
books.author: Ian W. Toll
books.thoughts: This book continues right from the last book. It provided a fantastic look into the history or the war in the Pacific.

books.title: Pacific Crucible
books.subTitle: War at Sea in the Pacific, 1941-1942
books.fullTitle: Pacific Crucible: War at Sea in the Pacific, 1941-1942
books.author: Ian W. Toll
books.thoughts: The Pacific Theater in WWII is something I wasn’t as familiar with compared to Europe. The writing was fantastic talking about the history of the big players involved and the actions taken at the beginning of the war by both the US and Japan. It was a great read to learn more about WWII and not dry reading either.

books.title: The Heart is a Lonely Hunter
books.fullTitle: The Heart is a Lonely Hunter
books.author: Carson McCullers
books.thoughts: I have a hard time giving my thoughts on this as it’s so far outside of my normal reading material. I enjoyed the story though and found the characters to be interesting.

books.title: Anansi Boys
books.author: Neil Gaiman
books.thoughts: I’m not sure whether I liked this better than American Gods, but it was an enjoyable read with some interesting characters.

books.title: American Gods
books.author: Neil Gaiman
books.thoughts: Ever read a book and struggle to define the synopsis? I can’t fully define the synopsis, but I enjoyed the story.

books.title: Liar’s Poker
books.author: Michael Lewis
books.thoughts: This was a lot different from his other books. It did provide an interesting look into one of the more famous names in Wall Street in the Saloman Brothers.

books.title: American Nations
books.subTitle: A History of the Eleven Rival Regional Cultures of North America
books.fullTitle: American Nations: A History of the Eleven Rival Regional Cultures of North America
books.author: Colin Woodard
books.thoughts: It was an interesting read talking about the history of the different areas of North America and how their founding and upbringing influence us even today. It was written over 10 years ago, but still hits the notes of the division we’re dealing with today.

books.title: The Bomber Mafia
books.subTitle: A Dream, a Temptation, and the Longest Night of the Second World War
books.fullTitle: The Bomber Mafia: A Dream, a Temptation, and the Longest Night of the Second World War
books.author: Malcolm Gladwell
books.thoughts: This was a good read, especially after having just finished The Bomb. It was interesting reading about how the different early Army Air Corps officers felt about and used their new weapons of war.

books.title: The Bomb
books.subTitle: Presidents, Generals, and the Secret History of Nuclear War
books.fullTitle: The Bomb: Presidents, Generals, and the Secret History of Nuclear War
books.author: Fred Kaplan
books.thoughts: This was an excellent read. It was interesting to see how the presidents from Truman to Trump thought about nuclear weapons and how we’ve managed to avoid using them. The work revealed from many in the Department of Defense and other experts was fascinating.

books.title: The Bond King
books.subTitle: How One Man Made a Market, Built an Empire, and Lost It All
books.fullTitle: The Bond King: How One Man Made a Market, Built an Empire, and Lost It All
books.author: Mary Childs
books.thoughts: I’ve heard of Pimco and of Bill Gross. This was an interesting read into his history and a bit of an internal look at trading companies.

books.title: Snow Crash
books.author: Neal Stephenson
books.thoughts: The “ultra-capitalist” future felt kind of weird. The story itself started off slow but picked up nicely. The ending was a little confusing and befuddling though.

books.title: Four Lost Cities
books.subTitle: A Secret History of the Urban Age
books.fullTitle: Four Lost Cities: A Secret History of the Urban Age
books.author: Annalee Newitz
books.thoughts: This was an interesting read on ancient cities. I had never even heard of two of the cities prior to reading this. It was an interesting look into the history of urban living, how it began and developed, and how these cities faded into history.

books.title: Weapons of Math Destruction
books.subTitle: How Big Data Increases Inequality and Threatens Democracy
books.fullTitle: Weapons of Math Destruction: How Big Data Increases Inequality and Threatens Democracy
books.author: Cathy O'Neil
books.thoughts: Most of what I read I was already aware of. Still, Cathy did a good job talking about what the issues with algorithms are, and why they can be problematic

books.title: What If? 2
books.author: Randall Munroe
books.thoughts: Randall Munroe does it again. He brings his scientific curiosity to the answer some pretty absurd questions. He does it with a good sense of humor and easy to understand language

books.title: Chokepoint Capitalism
books.subTitle: How Big Tech and Big Content Captured Creative Labor Markets and How We'll Win Them Back
books.fullTitle: Chokepoint Capitalism: How Big Tech and Big Content Captured Creative Labor Markets and How We'll Win Them Back
books.author: Cory Doctorow & Rebecca Giblin
books.thoughts: This was a fantastic read looking at how some of the tech and media giants have used the lack of competition to squeeze musicians, writers, developers and the rest of the creative industry. While this book only focuses on the creative industries, there are a lot of similarities all over. Cory and Rebecca do a good job explaining the problems, how we arrived at them, and what we can potentially do to even the playing field

books.title: The Data Detective
books.subTitle: Ten Easy Rules to Make Sense of Statistics
books.fullTitle: The Data Detective: Ten Easy Rules to Make Sense of Statistics
books.author: Tim Harford
books.thoughts: I've been a fan of Tim's writing. This book is no different. It's an interesting read helping give you some rules of thumb when reading about statistics and data. I know I've been guilty from time to time of some of the things one should avoid when being presented with data.

books.title: The Night the Lights Went Out
books.subTitle: A Memoir of Life After Brain Damage
books.fullTitle: The Night the Lights Went Out: A Memoir of Life After Brain Damage
books.author: Drew Magary
books.thoughts: I’ve always enjoyed Drew Magary’s writing on Defector and heard about his brush with death. This was an interesting memoir talking about his road back. Would recommend.

books.title: Responsible Javascript
books.author: Jeremy Wagner
books.thoughts: I know that I'm a little weak on making my websites more performant. This book did a good job talking about how to improve both JavaScript performance and examples of some things you can do to make your sites more user-friendly.

books.title: Walkaway
books.author: Cory Doctorow
books.thoughts: I've generally enjoyed Cory Doctorow's writing style. The story had an interesting premise even going so far as to touch on some of today's economic issues. Without giving too much away, some of the jumps in time were a little rough, but easy enough to follow. I enjoyed it, but it was not my favorite Doctorow novel.

books.title: Unit Testing Principles, Practices, and Patterns
books.fullTitle: Unit Testing Principles, Practices, and Patterns
books.author: Vladimir Khorikov
books.thoughts: I've been doing a lot more unit tests over the last year or two. This book did a good job going over how to write better tests and ways to improve the code to make tests better and easier to write. A good read for developers. The code examples are in C#, but the principals could be applied to other languages.

books.title: Moonshot
books.subTitle: Inside Pfizer’s Nine-Month Race to Make the Impossible Possible
books.fullTitle: Moonshot: Inside Pfizer’s Nine-Month Race to Make the Impossible Possible
books.author: Dr. Albert Bourla
books.thoughts: The book had a little too much of a “Rah Rah” feel to me which I guess isn’t surprising since it was written by Pfizer’s CEO. When I picked it up at the library I was hoping there’d be a little more meat to it.

books.title: The End of Everything
books.subTitle: (Astrophysically Speaking)
books.author: Katie Mack
books.thoughts: Being a space nut, this was a fun read learning about the various different ways the universe might end. Katie Mack did a fantastic job describing it with a good mix of humor and not-too-complicated language.

books.title: Born a Crime
books.author: Trevor Noah
books.thoughts: I appreciate Trevor’s comedy and the way he hosts The Daily Show. It was interesting reading about all he and his family had to deal with growing up in South Africa.

books.title: Project Hail Mary
books.author: Andy Weir
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this. It definitely had the same style as The Martian. The story had a good pace and was interesting.

books.title: The Passion Economy
books.subTitle: The New Rules for Thriving in the Twenty-First Century
books.fullTitle: The Passion Economy: The New Rules for Thriving in the Twenty-First Century
books.author: Adam Davidson
books.thoughts: This book wasn’t quite what I expected it to be, though looking back at it, I’m not entirely sure what I was expecting. It was still an interesting take on succeeding as a smaller business in the present day’s economy.

books.title: Dark Pools
books.subTitle: The Rise of the Machine Traders and the Rigging of the U.S. Stock Market
books.fullTitle: Dark Pools: The Rise of the Machine Traders and the Rigging of the U.S. Stock Market
books.author: Scott Patterson
books.thoughts: The stock market & computerized trading has become a fascination to me. This book does a great job talking about the rise of high-frequency trading and how it has caused some of the problems we see in the stock market today.

books.title: It's Better to Be Feared
books.subTitle: The New England Patriots Dynasty and the Pursuit of Greatness
books.fullTitle: It's Better to Be Feared: The New England Patriots Dynasty and the Pursuit of Greatness
books.author: Seth Wickersham
books.thoughts: I’m by no means a Patriots fan, but I found this to be an interesting look into the 2 decades long dynasty of Brady-Belichick and the Patriots.

books.title: The Storyteller
books.subTitle: Tales of Life and Music
books.fullTitle: The Storyteller: Tales of Life and Music
books.author: Dave Grohl
books.thoughts: Dave Grohl has always seemed to be an interesting and unique person. This was an interesting memoir talking about his growth from High School punk musician, through Nirvana and eventually Foo Fighters. If you’re a fan of any of his work, I’d highly recommend this.

books.title: Nudge
books.subTitle: The Final Edition
books.author: Richard Thaler, Cass Sunstein
books.thoughts: This was a fantastic read into how we as humans can be persuaded into doing things in ways we don’t always recognize. The authors do a good job going into the good and bad of it.

books.title: The Apollo Murders
books.author: Chris Hadfield
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this book. It had a good story that pulled you in. As a space fan, I definitely enjoyed the tie-ins with the Apollo program. The ending wasn’t my favorite part, but it did tidy up the story arcs. Would still recommend it to anyone.

books.title: Leviathan Falls
books.author: James S.A. Corey
books.thoughts: I did enjoy this as the final book in the series. Given that this is the end of a long series, I still haven’t come to a complete decision on how I feel about how the story was ended.

books.title: The Righteous Mind
books.subTitle: Why Good People Are Divided by Politics and Religion
books.fullTitle: The Righteous Mind: Why Good People Are Divided by Politics and Religion
books.author: Jonathan Haidt
books.thoughts: This was a dense read. While I’m not sure I understood everything, Jonathan Haidt’s explanation for why people act the way they do was thoughtful and interesting.

books.title: The Buyout of America
books.subTitle: How Private Equity Is Destroying Jobs and Killing the American Economy
books.fullTitle: The Buyout of America: How Private Equity Is Destroying Jobs and Killing the American Economy
books.author: Josh Kosman
books.thoughts: This book made me angry. It made me angry at how private equity firms have taken advantage of tax loopholes to make money at the cost of the little guys.

books.title: The Cult of We
books.subTitle: Wework, Adam Neumann, and the Great Startup Delusion
books.fullTitle: The Cult of We: Wework, Adam Neumann, and the Great Startup Delusion
books.author: Eliot Brown, Maureen Farrell
books.thoughts: I had heard all the stories about WeWork and its collapse. I didn't realize how crazy it actually was. The authors do a great job going into what was happening when and why things happened the way they did. I left amazed at how all the red flags Adam & WeWork had raised were ignored for so long.

books.title: Think Again
books.subTitle: The Power of Knowing What You Don't Know
books.fullTitle: Think Again: The Power of Knowing What You Don't Know
books.author: Adam Grant
books.thoughts: This book definitely made me think about how I view things and assumptions I might make.

books.title: The Premonition
books.subTitle: A Pandemic Story
books.author: Michael Lewis
books.thoughts: Reading this book made me realize how screwed we were by the COVID-19 pandemic. While there were plenty of heroes doing their best to help solve the issues, Michael Lewis does a good job showing why the organizations we trusted let us down.

books.title: Field of Schemes
books.subTitle: How the Great Stadium Swindle Turns Public Money Into Private Profit
books.fullTitle: Field of Schemes: How the Great Stadium Swindle Turns Public Money Into Private Profit
books.author: Neil deMause & Joanna Cagan
books.thoughts: I always knew that the public funding of sports stadiums was a raw deal. This book did a great job explaining how bad it is and how we got there.

books.title: Money
books.subTitle: The True Story of a Made-Up Thing
books.fullTitle: Money: The True Story of a Made-Up Thing
books.author: Jacob Goldstein
books.thoughts: As an avid listener of Planet Money and someone who's interested in economics, this was a fantastic read. It went into some interesting history in an easy to understand and light-hearted manner.

books.title: The MVP Machine
books.subTitle: How Baseball's New Nonconformists Are Using Data to Build Better Players
books.fullTitle: The MVP Machine: How Baseball's New Nonconformists Are Using Data to Build Better Players
books.author: Ben Lindbergh, Travis Sawchik
books.thoughts: Being a fan of baseball, this was a great read going into some of the details of how the game is changing away from 'Moneyball' and delving deep into player development.

books.title: Franchise
books.subTitle: The Golden Arches in Black America
books.fullTitle: Franchise: The Golden Arches in Black America
books.author: Marcia Chatelain
books.thoughts: I heard about this book on a podcast (Marketplace I believe) and learned a lot about the relationship between McDonalds and Black America that has been filled with ups and downs.

books.title: The 99% Invisible City
books.author: Roman Mars & Kurt Kohlstedt
books.thoughts: Having been listening to the 99% Invisible podcast for a long while, it was nice to read about more of the hidden designs in cities and towns.

books.title: The End is Always Near
books.author: Dan Carlin
books.thoughts: As a Hardcore History fan, Dan Carlin does a great job writing about close calls to having humanity being wiped out or the population dramatically reduced.

books.title: Head On
books.author: John Scalzi
books.thoughts: Solid detective novel and a good follow-up to Lock In.

books.title: The Last Emperox
books.author: John Scalzi
books.thoughts: Great novel to finish the trilogy. A great ending and worth the read.

books.title: The Consuming Fire
books.author: John Scalzi
books.thoughts: Solid continuation of the Interdependency Series by John Scalzi. Definitely made me want to continue reading.

books.title: The Collapsing Empire
books.author: John Scalzi
books.thoughts: This was a good start to a good science fiction trilogy. I'll have to finish it to be able to say more, but it definitely kept me hooked and wanting to continue.

books.title: The Age of Surveillance Capitalism
books.author: Shoshana Zuboff
books.thoughts: This was a long read, but thoughtful and complicated. It goes into how services like Google & Facebook take as much of our data as they possibly can even when it will disturb the general population. It also confirmed my reasons for deleting my Facebook and Instagram accounts as well as moving away from Google.

books.title: The Big Short
books.author: Michael Lewis
books.thoughts: This was a fantastic read talking about people looking into the real-estate market prior to the 2008 financial collapse. Michael Lewis did a great job of keeping the story interesting while also using language and terms that make the story understandable to anyone.

books.title: The Outsider
books.author: Stephen King
books.thoughts: I read this to get myself ready for the HBO series. I enjoyed the story and thought it provided a bit of supernatural mixed with just the right amount of suspense. If you're a Stephen King fan, you'll definitely enjoy this.

books.title: Open Borders
books.author: Bryan Caplan & Zach Weinersmith
books.thoughts: I don't think I would of expected something like this to have been done with a graphic novel, but it was anyway, and done well. It was an interesting read about the economics and some of the misunderstandings of immigration.

books.title: How To
books.author: Randall Munroe
books.thoughts: As a fan of XKCD and of Randall's humor, this book was informative and funny. Randall has a fantastic way of bringing science, humor, and the absurd together in an interesting and easy-to-read-and-understand way.

books.title: The Fifth Risk
books.author: Michael Lewis
books.thoughts: This book made me go back and forth between "wow, that's interesting!" and anger. I learned a lot about little (but actually big) things different departments within the U.S. Government does and the risks now in place due to the cronyism and general lack of knowledge the Trump Administration has introduced.

books.title: Auberon
books.author: James S.A. Corey
books.thoughts: Another solid novella set in the universe of The Expanse.

books.title: The Soul of America
books.author: Jon Meacham
books.thoughts: Reading this during Trump's presidency gave me some hope for the country being able to move forward. It reminded me of Martin Luther King's Quote "The arc of the moral universe is long, but it bends toward justice." It took a look back at previous tumultuous times in America and showed that while progress hasn't always been as fast as I would like, we as a nation have progressed.

books.title: Flash Boys
books.subTitle: A Wall Street Revolt
books.fullTitle: Flash Boys: A Wall Street Revolt
books.author: Michael Lewis
books.thoughts: I've been getting more interested in how the financial world works. This was a fantastic read about High-Frequency Trading and how it often screws over common investors like you and me. Michael Lewis then goes on to tell how one guy went about figuring this out to then trying to even the playing field.

books.title: The Incomplete Book of Running
books.author: Peter Sagal
books.thoughts: I've been a big fan of Peter Sagal ever since I started listening to Wait, Wait...Don't Tell Me! I'm also a fan of running. This is a fantastic read that is inspiring whether you're a runner or not. The book contains Sagal's wit and humor as well as some good life lessons.

books.title: Congo
books.author: Michael Crichton
books.thoughts: I enjoyed this one. Wasn't my favorite Crichton novel, but it was an interesting story with a plotline that had the right number of twists.

books.title: Sphere
books.author: Michael Crichton
books.thoughts: Continuing going through my Michael Crichton backlog, I wasn't super impressed with this one. It was a decent science fiction story with a bit of a horror element, but it didn't draw me in like some of his other novels.

books.title: Prey
books.author: Michael Crichton
books.thoughts: I really enjoyed this. The horror element mixed with the idea of nanotechnology provided for an excellent read.

books.title: The Andromeda Strain
books.author: Michael Crichton
books.thoughts: I enjoyed the story, and with me reading it during the lead up to the outbreak of COVID-19, it rang a little scary.

books.title: Us vs. Them
books.subTitle: The Failure of Globalism
books.fullTitle: Us vs. Them: The Failure of Globalism
books.author: Ian Bremmer

books.title: Working Futures
books.author: Mike Masnick & Others
books.thoughts: I enjoyed just about all the stories in this collection. Many of them rang true to what we could see come to fruition in the future.

books.title: Vietnam
books.subTitle: An Epic Tragedy, 1945-1975
books.author: Sir Max Hastings
